          soft-eng-request%xx.lcs.mit@TOR.nta.no,
          sun-spots-request@rice.edu, texhax-request@score.stanford.edu,
          works-request@rutgers.edu, pcip-request@udel.edu,
          security-request@aim.rutgers.edu, tcp-ip-request@sri-nic.arpa,
          protocols-request@rutgers.edu, apollo-request@umix.cc.umich.edu,
          header-people-request@mc.lcs.mit.edu,
          ifip-gtwy-request@tis.llnl.gov, info-modems-request@simtel20.arpa,
          ailist-request@ai.ai.mit.edu, info-hams-request@simtel20.arpa,
          esperanto-request@lll-crg.llnl.gov,
          transputer-request@tcgould.tn.cornell.edu
DATED   : 11 Aug 1988 at 2316 PDT
STATUS  : old, read

Speaking for Uninett (yes double T), a x.400 based research network in
Norway, and .no, the norwegian Internet domain, I announce that the
norwegian network society loose its only US Internet satellitte link on
Monday 15. of August.  This situation is expected to last until mid
October.

I kindly ask all list administrators to look up norwegian addresses in
their respective distribution list(s), particularly those containing
...%...uninett@tor.nta.no (nta-vax).  What I want you to do is route
mail distribution via BITNET to our BITNET gateway norunix.bitnet,
instead of tor.nta.no.  That is, the above address becomes e.g.
     ...%...uninett%norunix.bitnet@cunyvm.cuny.edu

(Inside BITNET, mail to the .no domain is always forwarded to norunix).

When I know more about the upcoming of our satellitte link, I will inform
you.

If you receive messages from other norwegians asking for similar actions,
I apologize.  If there are any questions I will attempt to answer.
Thank you for the patience.   

--Harald Eikrem   Runit, CC @ U of Trondheim, Norway
                  &lt;postmaster%vax.runit.unit.uninett@tor.nta.no&gt;
       becoming   &lt;postmaster%vax.runit.unit.uninett@norunix.bitnet&gt;
       

